               <head>Ovid's Metamorphoses in Italian and Hebrew</head>
               
               
               
               <msContents class="lccn.loc.gov/sh85070315" rend="visible">
                  
                  
                  
                  <summary>Ovid's Metamorphoses, books 1-3, in Italian and Hebrew translation.</summary>
                  
                  
                  
                  <textLang mainLang="he" otherLangs="ita"/>
                  
                  
                  
                  <msItem rend="">
                     
                     
                     
                     <locus from="1r" to="108v"/>
                     
                     
                     
                     <title xml:lang="en">Metamorphoses</title>
                     
                     
                     
                     <title xml:lang="he">שירי החליפות</title>
                     
                     
                     
                     <author>
                        
                        
                        
                        <persName xml:lang="en" key="viaf.org/viaf/88342447">Ovid, 43 B.C.-17 18 A.D</persName>
                        
                        
                        
                        <persName xml:lang="he" key="viaf.org/viaf/88342447">אובידיוס נזו, פובליוס</persName>
                     
                     
                     
                     </author>
                     
                     
                     
                     <note>
                        
                        
                        
                        <p>In the Italian version of Giovannin Andrea dell' Anguillara and the Hebrew translation of ot by Shabtai Marini (a rabbi and physician at Padua, 18th century), in parallel columns.</p>
                        
                        
                        
                        <p>Like the Italian, the Hebrew translation is arranged in stanzas of eight lines each, with regular rhymes.</p>
                        
                        
                        
                        <p>Folio 1 contains an introductory poem in fourteen eight-lined stanzas, by the translator, followed by a sonnet in praise of him.</p>
                        
                        
                        
                        <p>Book 2 begins on folio 29r, book 3 on folio 70r.</p>
                     
                     
                     
                     </note>
                  
                  
                  
                  </msItem>
               
               
               
